The current movement protesting against Dutch rules quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region except for foreign journalists or civil rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with independent Papua New Guinea occupying the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a remote and desolate city, which can be reached after a ninety-minute flight from the capital of Jayapura province to Nabire, and then a five-hour stomach-wrenching ride.
Mass transit doesn't work in this place.
The city of 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs made of woolen sheets in shades of gray and rusty color.
Very few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and virtually no foreigners have visited this place.
Prior to the arrival of Christians, locals worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
“We weren’t used to wearing this dress,” says Bardina, pointing to her colorful, hand-knit turban, dark T-shirt, and shiny skirt.
"We used to only carry leaves."
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line and child mortality and literacy being among the worst in all of Asia.
At the same time, it is an Indonesian land of gold.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of America's Phoeenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai - a rocky province approximately the size of New Jersey, home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports an estimated $78 billion worth of logging.
However, these riches are a source of suffering for Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian army.
An investigation conducted by the New York Times in 2005 found that Freeport paid local military officials and troops about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 for one officer.
Papuans calling for self-government are threatening this golden goose and are therefore being severely suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
The mass murders in the Papuan tribal area during the 1970s amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful Protestants in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes the atrocities that occurred last year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture - according to another report, particularly popular rape and electrocution - and brutal repression of peaceful protesters.
“It’s difficult to calculate the death toll because incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The situation is aggravated by the fact that Papuan sources attract colonists to Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants, 83% are Christian, but demographics change with the influx of Muslim immigrants from Indonesia's islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, or a mixture of vegetables with peanut sauce.
Local people are struggling to survive.
“Immigrants have started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,” said Abeth You, 24, who was born in Paniai and moved to the capital of Jayapura province to work.
"The original inhabitants of Papua - mama-mama (women) - have thus lost their jobs."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, promised to address inequality and rights violations during his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter secured and made his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua and the local people feel betrayed.
“Our hearts have been broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi with the hope that he will listen to our call for justice,” You said.
The fact is that just two months after Jakowi’s inauguration in October, Paniai experienced a major shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children sang Christmas songs by a campfire in the town of Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers emerged from the twilight of night on motorbikes.
Two of the surprised children told them that they should turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by the reprimand and tone, and later returned with four other soldiers, local parish priest Yavedt Tebai said.
Two of the soldiers in a drunken state chased a group of children and beat them with the butts of their guns, the victims and witnesses of the event said.
One of the soldiers then fired on a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a nearby Electoral Commission building, and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and army headquarters, demanding justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed a waita dance - in which they run in a circle and imitate the singing of birds - of the Papuan tribe Mee Pago.
Several Protestants began throwing stones at the buildings.
With increasing tension, soldiers were ordered via radio: “If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are allowed to shoot,” according to the TIME weekly in an official document, the contents of which were never published in the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, head of the Enarotali district of Kego Koto, recognized the imminent danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
But no one listened to his words.
“When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist,” he told TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame does not yet know who the shooter was, but according to him, the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
“There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting,” he added.
One resident, Alfius Youw, said his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, was shot three times.
“I ran to my body to make sure it was him,” Yohanes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME.
“I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.”
The Papuan police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were merely “providing” for the station that was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten us with death,” said Pudjo Sulistiya, a spokesman for the Papuan police.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many were injured.
The news of the murders slid through Jakarta's media the following day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his understanding for the victims' families and promising to address the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it can never be repeated," he said.
National Security Minister Wiranto announced in October 2016 that he would introduce an out-of-court mechanism to resolve acts of violence that occurred in the past.
Almost immediately, there were excuses.
“Most of the violence happened a long time ago.
Some of them happened in the 1990s and some at the beginning of the 21st century.
I mean, we are determined to punish these violent acts, but it will not be an easy task," he said.
However, in a June 5 interview for the TIME weekly, held in Jakarta, Wiranto claimed that he had no plans to implement any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said, “all cases will be brought to court.”
Wiranto, who was accused by the UN of “crimes against humanity” after more than 1,000 deaths during the 1999 independent elections in East Timor, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua, including the Paniai incident, had been settled so far.
The families of the victims of the Paniai shooting welcomed his claims with mistrust.
“I’ve been asked four times in the last three years, but I haven’t seen anything yet,” Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
A few years later, he still lives in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says himself.
“I’m afraid the army will arrest me or someone will shoot me.”
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many of the Paniai residents, who are afraid to speak out about the incident.
He said he was beaten by members of the military after helping to bury four of the victims.
“After the bodies were buried, the army started looking for me,” he said.
And the shooting is still going on.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in neighboring Deiyai.
A skirmish in which one person died and 17 others were injured occurred between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to provide assistance in transporting an unconscious man to a hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died en route to hospital.
Angry villagers protested outside the company's building.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at the members and were given warning shots in response.
Local residents, however, claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) began firing into the crowd, killing one person.
“There was panic, we were afraid of retaliation,” 29-year-old Domingogu Badia, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the arrival of the injured, told TIME.
“I didn’t leave the house for two days.”
The Deiyai parliament demanded the punishment of the police officers involved and the withdrawal of the mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the side of the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal indigenous peoples who live in the central highlands.
Many have joined the Papuan Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of insurgents that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and abducting Indonesian police officers.
Some of the leaders of the OPM come from Paniai. They include Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks, the military has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of residents of Paniai in recent years, all under the pretext of “ensuring national sovereignty”.
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known among the people of Papua as a “tragic and forgotten place”.
