The lack of news from foreign journalists means that international pressure on Indonesia in the Papuan case is largely limited.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands - urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread acts of violence" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported the OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the allegations, telling reporters in Jakarta that "In Indonesia, the democratic system is still in place and the media are free, so it is difficult to disguise evidence of human rights violations."
Local people are calling for the participation of foreign governments.
When the official delegation from the Netherlands, headed by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, the local people shouted, according to a source who also attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous, the slogan "we want freedom".
More elections are planned in Indonesia for 2019, but the Papuans say they will not vote for Jokowi.
“Jokowi is a person who has good intentions but is surrounded by people associated with the Paniai shooting,” said Gobau, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai - in addition to living in constant fear of a robber army - are wallowing in poverty, poor education and a health system.
Gobai claims that the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote a “debt” that Jokowi must repay.
“They don’t want money, they want justice,” he added.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting continue their last symbolic act of defiance: they bury the bodies of the victims on the property opposite the police and army station.
Knowing that justice will never be done for enough, he will at least not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"A member of our family has been killed," Yacobus said with his head down.
"What can we do?"
