EPA chief Scott Pruitt on delaying plans to cut Obama administration emissions
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by 15 states, its chief Scott Pruitt withdrew his earlier decision to delay the implementation of the former Obama administration's plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt introduced changes to his plan to respond more swiftly than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
However, he did not mention the legal challenge filed against his previous position in the federal appeals court.
This concerns the latest deadline, set for October 1, when countries should start to comply with the 2015 regulation for reducing ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the deal for one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid "interference with local decisions or threatened economic growth."
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma’s attorney general before President Donald Trump was installed as EPA chief, has long served as a staunch opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industries.
The sudden turnaround on Wednesday is the biggest legal setback for Pruitt's regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA’s executor had overstepped his authority in an attempt to delay incorporating the Obama administration’s plan, which required oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed his version of the ozone standards and strengthened the EPA's commitment to working with states through complex processes and meeting new standards within a given timeframe.
“Under the previous administration, the EPA often missed deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set plans,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
“We don’t believe in regulation through litigation, and we take compliance seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it."
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point use "the possibility of delay and all other legally available authorities" to ensure that regulations "are based on sound policy and the most accessible information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a more comprehensive rewrite of the ozone rules.
The White House budget approved last month seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure still hasn't passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed a coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group does not intend to allow in legal coercion.
"The EPA's turnaround - following our lawsuit - is an important victory for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution," Schneiderman added.
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington, and Washington, D.C. joined New York.
Ground-level ozone occurs when common harmful substances emitted by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants, and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists applaud Pruitt's sudden change.
“It’s worrying how much pressure we need to exert to change the minds of those in charge and protect the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to grapple with the ideological pull of the Trump administration to help polluters and special interests.”
