Since 2005, a group of activists have returned to Moore’s Ford Bridge to reenact the fateful night in 1946 when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Kuklux Klan.
No one has yet been tried for the murders.
"It's surprising that not a single person has been arrested in all these years - even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identity," Brooks said in a statement.
"It's a stain on our history and a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and lifelong civil rights campaigner.
In his eyes, the reenactment of the event presents a dramatic call to action, reminding the Monroe community every year that justice has not been done enough.
"We demand prosecution and closure, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but above all justice," Brooks said.
“Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin.”
The medical examiner covers one of the bodies of the victims of the lynching at Moore's Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were to attend the lynching.
No one has yet been prosecuted.
Despite the fact that the suspects remain at large for decades, civil rights advocates say both the politics and sex were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court granted Georgia blacks the right to vote for the first time in an election scheduled for the summer.
It was during the summer election that black farmer Roger Malcom allegedly stabbed white landowner Barnett Hester during a skirmish, according to the FBI.
In the city, according to Brooks, it was rumored that Hester was having sex with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and brought her to a different state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison posted a $600 bail for Malcolm.
He was accompanied to the prison by Dorothy and cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
Returning from the prison, just before the entrance to the Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
