“It is also clear that there was a collusion between state and local law enforcement officials, who not only participated in the lynching, but also disposed of the evidence and concealed the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks made the point more succinctly.
"It was a massacre because of the right to vote," he said.
“The murders had a clear subtext for all black locals: ‘This is what you’ll get if you sign up and vote.’”
The annual reconstruction of the event at Moore's Ford Bridge has been organized for nearly a decade by Cassandra Greene.
Her performance is figurative, engaging, and concise, showing a deep-seated racism that many would like to see extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction isn't easy, and it's even harder to look away, but Greene says it makes sense.
“Nobody wants to talk about lynching, because in doing so, we have to face the uncomfortable feelings that lurk in each of us,” Greene said.
“But we can’t have a relationship unless you listen to what I’ve been through.”
