The aim of the method is a more accurate assessment of applicants in the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted 6,880 cases for investigation, and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests conducted between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were judged to be over 18, while a further 25 cases were judged by the Forensic Medical Agency to be “possibly over 18.”
In a further 423 cases, it was decided that the interviewee was “possibly under 18 years of age.”
Tests are only taken if the age of the interviewee is questionable.
According to Johan Goransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond with the previous month.
“Compared to last month, the statistics are still on track and the numbers are very similar,” he told The Local.
The higher number of applicants estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers are lying about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests, saying that in 442 cases, “the person in question is 18 years of age or older.”
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases, the interviewee said he would turn 18 this year.
The medical method of determining age, which includes X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of the knee joints, has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, which is concerned, among other things, with assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age when the person passed puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue and I don’t think these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we can’t determine age with accuracy, we shouldn’t pretend otherwise,” he told Metro.
The agency said: “In general, the risk of a child being misjudged as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the interviewee is just under 18 years old, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all interviewees."
