Sebastian Coe praises Russia’s ‘sincere’ apology for doping scandal
Former top athlete Sebastian Coe praised Russia on Thursday for its sincere apology for the doping scandal, but reiterated that it was not yet the right time for Russia to return to the sports world.
The head of Russian athletics Dmitry Shylakhtin said on the occasion of the IAAF congress - which took place on the eve of the World Championships in Athletics - that the expulsion of his country from the world of sports was correct and that he is determined to fight doping.
He apologized to “all the athletes who lost gold and silver medals in this way.”
Despite his comments, members of the IAAF Congress voted to uphold the ban, which came into effect in November 2015 after a report by the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) showed that Russia had supported doping for its athletes.
“I think we saw a very honest response and presentation today,” IAAF President Sebastian Coe told reporters.
"All the members of the council and the congress were pleasantly surprised that Russia admitted its mistake and is working with all its might to correct and restore the proper functioning of the entire Federation."
Coe said he was also “delighted” that Russia had accepted the criteria for its reintroduction.
“I think today has been very successful and we have taken it to the next level, but the Congress supports the recommendation of the Crisis Staff to maintain the punishment that has been imposed on Russia,” Coe said.
“In the coming months, we need to do everything we can to stabilize the situation.
Our aim has always been to separate honest athletes from dishonest ones," he concluded.
At the World Championships in Athletics, which begins in London on Friday, 19 Russian athletes who have complied with strict IAAF rules will compete under a neutral flag.
IAAF crisis chief Rune Andersen said on Monday that Russia still had to meet several criteria before it could be allowed back in.
Drug tests are still unsatisfactory and the expelled coaches continue to operate, he told reporters in London after the IAAF board's presentation.
