How the Financial Rules of Football Will Affect Neymar's Move to Paris
Rules restricting the funding of European football clubs will not disrupt Neymar’s record transfer from Barcelona to Paris-Saint Germain.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by the EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to prohibit teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
The Financial Fair Play Rules (FFP) introduced by UEFA in 2011 stipulate that PSG will have to prove that Neymar's transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid 222 million euros just to buy Neymar out of his contract, and Neymar will demand a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
The following are a few financial terms for Neymar's move to France.
Since the PSG team is funded by a wealthy Qatari family who have become wealthy on energy sales, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already stellar football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums to buy players, but on the other hand they have to prove legal sources of income, which allows them to cover the overhead costs of business activities related to football.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini when he was appointed UEFA Director in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs in pursuit of new reinforcements were ultimately cheating and risking bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, FFP's rules shifted its attention from club debts to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spend exorbitant sums for y players to build a global brand - suddenly wasn't so profitable.
Under the current three-year trial period, which ends in 2018, clubs can report a loss of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite the fact that Platini had to leave his post in 2015, his successor Aleksander Ceferin is determined to advocate a ban on excessive spending.
“The FFP rules are still in place and we are committed to strengthening them in the future,” Andrea Traverso, who oversees compliance with the FFP rules, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG has paid the amount for Neymar’s redemption in a one-time payment, it may spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract for accounting purposes.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down to EUR 44.4 million annually for five years.
The first wave of the FFP's top sanctions hit PSG in 2014 along with Manchester City, which is owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG was fined 60 million euros ($82 million) - which was later reduced to 20 million euros - and the order to reduce the Champions League squad to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is wary of teams that may attempt to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their revenues through companies affiliated with club owners.
Thus, even though the Qatari company sponsors PSG, once the funding exceeds the value of the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the settlement of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after it decided that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
Some of Neymar's earnings at PSG could be reimbursable from the 2022 FIFA World Cup organizing committee in Qatar, according to some reports.
PSG and officials at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar, however, denied a fat that Neymat should become an ambassador for the World Cup and that such a maneuver would be easily detected by UEFA officials.
The previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempts to circumvent the rules.
UEFA officials said Tuesday that it has not opened an investigation into Neymar's transfer to PSG.
The source of the report wished to remain anonymous as he is not allowed to comment on the situation with PSG, The Associated Press reported.
The latest published financial statements show that PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of EUR 10 million and a turnover of EUR 542.4 million.
The financial statements for the current financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar’s arrival to be a huge opportunity for sponsors, merchandising and jersey sales.
The club expects to increase turnover by up to 30 percent from the signing of the contract.
Spanish league officials, obviously concerned about the departure of one of the biggest stars, sought to thwart Neymar's departure, arguing that PSG would violate FFP rules.
“This is a clear case of ‘financial doping’ for the club and the state,” Javier Teba, president of the la Liga, told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to the club’s ownership by the Qatari syndicate.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's stance on financing the club.
“This is the result of ownership that has fundamentally changed the football world over the last 15 years,” Wenger said.
“Once a club owner becomes a club owner, anything is possible.
