NHS prescribes controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
Starting in September, patients will have access to ‘transformative’ treatments to prevent HIV, following a Supreme Court ruling on funding for the NHS drug.
The National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to fund a trial period after an appeals court backed the Supreme Court's ruling last year, saying the NHS had the funds to pay PrEP despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was taken by NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a 'significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Other clinics will join in October and will be fully implemented across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among patients at risk.
PrEP before sex means that there are enough specific drugs in the patient’s body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
The clinics will identify eligible participants who will sign up to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GPs in the UK can also apply at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will come to taxpayers for ?10 million, and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute medicines after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It’s another milestone in more than 30 years of trying to stop one of the biggest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust, said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
When administered correctly and to patients at risk, PrEP will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
Starting in September, NSH will offer patients who are at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to receive this statement."
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The number one priority must be to quickly deploy tests across the country; we need to ensure it is available to every patient.
We now have PrEP, a trial drug, and we are well on our way to protecting the more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV.”
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to end the spread of HIV in society together.”
High Leg Life: Mezzanine and Smart Design Turn This Tiny Apartment into a Spacious Home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, swapped a big house in Knightsbridge for an apartment on Earls Cour in 2014.
Located on the first floor of the Queen Anne Smart Terrace, it showcases a modern design that makes the most of the space available.
“Before that, I lived with my ex-husband in a much larger house in Knightsbridge,” Joanne said.
“I was looking for something more reasonable.
I ran into this apartment in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I immediately fell in love with him and gave him a nod the same day.”
Since then, the apartment of 1000 square meters has undergone a complete renovation.
A one-room apartment with a complicated layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - Joanne wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceiling.
“I wanted a high ceiling, large windows and lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
To this end, she employed Erfan Azadi from the Duck & Shed design studio based in Notting Hill and used the almost four-metre ceiling to create a home that was not just a project but also a place to live.
The ceiling was not so high that two gaps could fit above each other - the challenge for architects was to create a mezzanine on which one could walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
“The steel structure is quite complicated,” he explained.
“We had to organize both spaces so that we could walk upright.
It was not only about building a simple platform, but at the same time bend the steel structure so that at the right height above and below the ceiling."
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - and at the same time add to the drama.
On the mezzanine, the beautiful living room overlooks the old copper window frames in Retrouvius design.
Mirror furniture in gold, silver lines and retro chandelier Serge Mouille creates a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor is equipped with mirrors on both sides and looks longer.
The mirror bar in the kitchen looks like a window to the next room.
At the front door there are storage areas equipped with mirrors for storing cutlery and glasses.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of a significantly larger space, is the possibility of separating it from the kitchen, if it is not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
What is unique about this solution, however, is the folding door.
“We had to figure out the technical side,” Erfan says of the reinforced veneered doors.
“The doors are fitted with a counterweight, so that it is very easy to roll off.”
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage space, Joanne got another 16 square meters, a second room and a better overall layout of the apartment.
"When it comes down to it, what you're selling is living space - or valuing your property," Erfan said.
“Basically, a real estate agent will calculate its price on the basis of the living space when entering an apartment.”
In this case, we managed to increase the living area while maintaining quality materials that give the space a luxurious look.
“Material is very important because you touch it and create an emotional bond with home,” Erfan added.
“You don’t love the electricity on the walls.
Yes, they are important, but your heart will not win."
As it turned out, the quality design and increase in living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional piece of work.
And like Joanne, you can choose to stay.
