Trump's new chief of staff plans to cut media diet
Many have tried before him and have always failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can actually do it.
If so, it will be the first.
Politico said the new White House chief of staff is planning to cut the flow of information from President Trump, including news reports, in hopes of keeping him afloat.
Here's a piece of Josh Dawsey's report:
“When the new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly met with staff on his first day in office, he outlined a key issue for the Trump White House that he intends to fix: misinformation that gets into the president’s hands.
Kelly told employees that he must personally approve all information - whether on paper or verbally - because the president can make better decisions based on the right information."
Kelly’s diagnosis actually makes sense, but many of his predecessors have broken their teeth at Trump’s scrutiny and media presentation.
Trump's relationship with the media dates back decades - and now that he's sitting in the White House, his habit of watching TV news is even stronger.
“If Trump as a candidate was upset by the honest reports, it was appropriate to show him that there were a lot of other media that were easier to convince,” Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri of Politico wrote at the time that "the key to keeping Trump's tweets in check - in the words of at least six former campaign organisers - is to ensure that Trump is regularly followed by media outlets that praise him."
All right.
But the idea that Trump’s tendency to post his views on Twitter was ever “under control” is ridiculous.
Maybe these campaign organizers know something that others don’t, that Trump’s tweets would have been more outrageous if they hadn’t been checked.
Tweets that Trump never sent will most likely never be known.
If his employees managed to keep him at bay at least a few times, then their efforts did not go to waste.
But so far, no one has been able to regularly prevent Trump from instigating controversial topics.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, which is made up of rival factions, people regularly try to strengthen their agenda by pushing Trump materials - which may or may not be reliable - that support their worldview.
Politico, which covered the issue from all sides, published a report in May on the inclination of advisers to submit dubious information to the head of state.
This is an example of such information from the pen of reporter Shane Goldmacher:
“Current and former Trump administration officials say the president often reacts very angry with negative media reports, especially leaks, and seeks to find their origin.
This situation occurred at the end of February when someone planted a copy of an article from GotNews.com - the website of provocateur Charles C. Johnson - that accused Assistant Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the "source of many leaks" from the White House.
Regardless, Johnson was banned from Twitter forever for harassment; or that he didn’t substantiate his claims with any evidence; or that he had already made false allegations in the past and later retracted them.
Trump read the article and started asking questions about Walsh."
Goldmacher said then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Secretary Rob Porter were “trying to implement a system to manage and document the information that President Trump receives.”
Would that work?
Now, three months later, Kelly is pursuing the same strategy.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump’s impulsivity is not going away, and his aides are still vying for power.
These immutable factors will certainly make Kelly's mission more difficult.
