“It will certainly go down in history as one of the most beautiful and well-preserved dinosaur species, the Mona Lisa dinosaurs.”
By studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore - despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank - was very likely facing a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used the camouflage system used by many of today's animals.
Experts say that this allowed him to better blend in with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The camouflage system suggests that he was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
News of the 110-million-year-old dinosaur of the family Nodosauridae first appeared in the newspaper in May. It is currently available for viewing at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who along with the team spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shape of scales and armor all over the body.
They discovered a method of camouflage commonly used by today's animals in defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the researchers’ findings are surprising because Borealopelta’s size far exceeds today’s animals using the same technique.
Thus, it is possible that the dinosaur was so numerous that evolution chose camouflage over confrontation to survive.
Many of today's camouflaged animals - such as deer, zebra and armadillo - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus had to literally fight for its survival.
“The sale of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur illustrates the dangers posed by Cretaceous-era predators,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic components in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur skin was likely reddish-brown in color.
The researchers continue to study the animal and search for other knowledge about its life, including preserved stomach contents, to track down its last meal.
He believes that the dinosaur fell into the river after death and was carried to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
