She had to know it and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
It needed to develop not only in activism and organizing, but also in knowing the difference between the different layers of black experience and what we need to do to be free.
Although I am able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism firsthand, she is in no way different from any other black child-woman.
I feel that if I protected her from this experience, I would only harm her."
Upon arrival in Ferguson, the first stop was on the South Florissant Road across from the police department, which became a base of activists awaiting police officer Darren Wilson's words about his possible involvement in the incident.
Here Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who was preparing food for others.
Together they prepared food in bags and helped to distribute it to Protestants.
In Ferrell’s eyes, a new type of activism slowly began to emerge.
“My activism turned upside down after August 9,” Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. association and sought to introduce health care and food to black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural."
A few weeks later, Ferrell met the documentary's later co-director, Sabaah Folayan, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and his cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "just document" the ongoing events.
Ferrell thought, “Are you working on a documentary or are you trying to find a story to use?”
This type of skepticism permeated the community through many people, often whites, who wanted to capitalize on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an interview: “We have heard that the voices of people who are born and raised in Ferguson are very often neglected and we wanted to change that.”
Folayano has already partnered with co-director Damon Davis, a respected local artist who deals with the topic of death row inmates.
His participation in the project also involved Ferrell and six other local residents, who were watched by the Whose Streets team in the years following Brown's assassination.
“No one speaks for us in this document, but it’s our testimony,” Davis said.
"That was important to me - how these people will be represented - because in the same way I will be represented."
While the goal of the documentary was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences - in an attempt to show that the movement "is not about a savior leader, but about bringing the community closer together," Folayano said - it turned out she was the most open to participating in the filming.
The documentary "Whose Streets?" describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell's life, such as how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said with a smile on her face when she saw the final version of the documentary.
“But I understood that in order to do this job and humanize black people, I had to open up.”
In addition, Ferrell’s story highlights the role of the eccentric black woman in the broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - who created the #BlackLivesMatter campaign in response to the killing of teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 on social media - call themselves weirdos.
“Black outlandish women in leadership positions ultimately stand behind the preservation of the movement,” Ferrell said, “because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the brunt of these events."
Folayane agrees with this statement, adding that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a large number of eccentric black women."
However, she insists that “this is not a mere affirmative action” and Ferrell is not the main character of the documentary because of her views.
“It was the driving force and the source of energy,” she said.
“It’s no coincidence that she’s on the front lines, because life at these intersections is dangerous in the skin of a black weirdo woman.
You can feel the energy in front of the screen.”
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, TV station cameras have cleared their positions, but the heavy racial ties between the community and the police persist.
Ferrell is serving two-and-a-half years for blocking a highway during demonstrations.
She described the socio-political atmosphere in the area she calls home as "a mess."
Yet she continues to make the commitment she’s made since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
All we have to lose are our chains.”
