A Becoming Resemblance: Artist Creates Portraits Using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery, there are several faces of different shades of skin - white, black and dark - suspended from the ceiling on wires. Each of them seems to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were made by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples to Fort Leavenworth, where she is serving a 35-year sentence for illegally posting classified cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience with technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before his departure from the US presidency.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning’s DNA, and by using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on the pliability of DNA - as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken of herself as a woman since her youth. She was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including six espionage laws, computer fraud, and theft.
All of her photographs were held by prison officials, and only one lower-quality black-and-white photo was released, in which Manning, visibly concerned, sits in the driver's seat in the platinum-blonde wig she is now associated with.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg’s 2012 Stranger Visions project continued to respond positively.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create a picture of possible forms of these people.
It was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to complete the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg said in a statement.
However, visits and photography were not allowed, so they asked Chelsea if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends within two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic strip called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the show in person.
Indeed, President Obama asked for Manning’s release a few days after the comic was published, which was a welcome change after several excruciating years in a Kansas military prison.
Interestingly, the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging a war with people who seek to expose government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to incite resentment with his tweets in areas he should be supporting.
In response to a question about this special timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that “everything happens for a reason.”
Under the artist’s statement on one of the gallery’s walls, Manning’s huge signature (the letter “i” in the surname is dotted with the heart) calls for an end to “self-acting factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality, and culture.”
On the opposite side there are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - centipede letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist’s sophisticated scientific vocabulary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
“I hope that people will learn from this that our genome doesn’t matter who we are and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way,” Dewey-Hagborg said.
“DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them.”
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is a single page from the aforementioned graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging as King Kong from the United States Disiplinary Barracks prison with a megaphone in her hand.
“As soon as they stop you from speaking, they win,” she says.
“Never be silenced.”
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not yet personally visited the exhibition - as predicted in the comics - but when she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room with her masks, her own genomic effigies, lined up like a mob of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maninga on which her genetic haplogroups are written in pencil.
“In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted them to radiate a sense of crowd,” Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates her.”
Northwestern University professor and Oxford University employee wanted for murder
A nationwide search is underway for a Northwestern University professor and Oxford University staffer who are being prosecuted on suspicion of murdering a man found stabbed to death in a luxury Chicago apartment, police said.
On Monday, a first-degree murder warrant was issued for a man named Wyndham Lathem (42) and Andrew Warren (56) for their alleged complicity in the death of Trenton H. James Cornell-Duranleau, according to the Cook County court file.
Cornell-Duranleau, 26, died of multiple stab wounds.
Chicago police said the body was found on July 27.
Upon arrival at the Grand Plaza Apartments, they found the victim in one of the apartments with several lacerations.
Cornell-Duranleau has been pronounced dead at the scene and detectives are investigating the case as a homicide, while police are searching for both suspects, authorities said.
Lathem has worked as associate professor of microbiology and immunology at Northwestern University since 2007.
Alan K. Cubbage, the university's vice president of public relations, said in an email that Lathem is now on administrative leave and has been banned from the university's campuses.
“The relevant authorities are now investigating the matter and Northwestern University is fully cooperating with them,” Cubbage said.
Warren is an executive financial administrator at Oxford University.
A spokesman for the university and Somerville College said in a statement sent by e-mail: “We have been contacted by the British police and we are ready to assist the US police as well.”
The statement also said Warren’s colleagues were shocked and wanted him to report to the police.
Anthony Guglielmi, the Chicago Police Department's head of public relations, said he was calling on suspects to surrender to the appropriate authorities.
"Police have information about their whereabouts and efforts to track down suspects are escalating," Guglielmi said.
Guglielmi said local, regional and national authorities are assisting in the search for suspects.
According to Guglielmi, police received a call from the manager of the Grand Plaza building, who was alerted to the events that were to occur in apartment no. 1008.
Police described the scene as very violent.
Guglielmi said it was unclear if the incident occurred on July 27.
He added that Lathe and Warren were captured by security cameras.
"We believe that Professor Latham knew his victim," Guglielmi said.
Grand Plaza issued a statement to all residents: "Police are now working to compile a timeline and profile of the victim and are investigating various motives, including domestic violence."
"In the near future, we will complete the plan of WADA" - Deputy Prime Minister of Russia Mutko
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said it would not be long before the remaining criteria of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) and the re-establishment of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) would be implemented.
“Currently, part of the criteria of the new plan has been completed and RUSADA has already been granted planning and testing rights in cooperation with the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
With this in mind, the WADA plan has been updated," Mutko said on Thursday.
The Vice-President commented on the second part of the WADA plan to comply with the Code - which describes the criteria for the renewal of RUSADA - which was recently published on the organization's website.
According to Mutko, the code does not contain anything that Russia should be concerned about.
“Everything has been announced and everything will be implemented.
The results will be made available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future."
However, one of the criteria calls for the public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation investigated by Richard McLaren about the government’s alleged sponsorship of doping by Russian athletes.
On the subject, Mutko said: “We are conducting an investigation because our anti-doping system has obviously failed.
All measures were taken.
But there were no state programs in our country, and so we can’t confess to something that never existed.”
Mutko was confirmed by Vitaly Smirnov, director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russia’s RSport, Smirnov acknowledged the problems of Russian anti-doping officials, but added: “We have stated on many occasions that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report without reservation," Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected Russia of carrying out doping controls within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
However, the organization authorized planning and unification of testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) this June.
Following a visit to the organization's Moscow headquarters in July, WADA CEO Olivier Niggli said RUSADA was "on the right track" to renew.
