Police have charged three men with setting fire to a rare wooden church in Třinec-Guty in the Frýdek-Místek region on Wednesday.
One of the accused is a minor, all three are Czech nationals.
They face up to 15 years in prison for the offence of general endangerment.
Moravian-Silesian Police Director Tomáš Kužel told journalists today.
He said it was an intentional crime.
"This is a very fresh matter and the police are currently working on the motive for the whole matter," said Kužel.
He said police would discuss possible arrests of the accused.
Further information, according to the director, cannot be disclosed.
"I can't say more yet, because the criminal police and investigation service and the prosecutor who oversees the case are really working on the matter," said Kužel.
The wooden church of the Body of Christ in Guty dates from the 16th century.
It was a valuable monument with many original furnishings and paintings from the first half of the 16th century.
According to preliminary estimates, material damage will amount to tens of millions of crowns, but the historical loss is incalculable.
Soon after the fire, the restoration of the church was considered.
Most of the costs should be covered by insurance, other costs are ready to be shared with the Ministry of Culture and the city, a public collection is also being prepared and the contribution of the owner of the monument, i.e. the local parish, is expected.
