More money would go to salaries or to build an information system.
The proposal also foresees the need to expand the scope of regional military headquarters, which would together employ another 42 soldiers.
Ministry officials have previously said the law should also help resolve some Czech politicians' disagreement with the introduction of a European Union directive on gun ownership.
Its adoption would allow shooters who will be part of the system to retain some of the weapons prohibited by the directive.
Start-ups that will help your company not to become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but she didn’t find the appropriate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even deceptive.
And despite promising the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their disbelief in the entire process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
She asked for help from outside.
New human resources startups are constantly appearing on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intent of measuring employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographics, offer complete employee anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass supervisors and contact directors directly.
“There are tools like Strava and Fitbit on the market that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said she has gained more awareness of what her employees think and feel over the past three years.
In addition to quick surveys and voting specific teams, Glint offers a temperature map of the company and a quick overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of the managers with low ratings - allowing the user to work on the correction.
Companies are starting to realize the need to heed the culture of the workplace - in case they become the next Uber - that is being swept up in scandals after a former employee posted on his blog a post describing the corporate environment and the harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to technical and financial progress website Let’s Talk Payments, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Convercent, a Denver, Colorado-based startup that helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small surge in interest and activity earlier this year, just ahead of the Uber scandals.
Nearly 600 of Convercent’s clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has also recently taken over.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable “flash” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
Where the Director General is involved, complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
“The court of public opinion has empowered regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behavior - and regulators do not intervene - it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, employee exhaustion, or lawsuits, Quinlan added.
Employing more than 25,000 people across 500 locations, the Ruby Tuesday restaurant network has been using Convercent for more than a year to increase employee awareness of corporate policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate executives.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to find a phone number or e-mail to the company management, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful resolution.
It was often a discouraging and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, general counsel of Ruby Tuesday, according to which there had not previously been a reliable way to monitor employees' complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, quick detection and resolution of issues that have never before been found by office managers is a long way from the actual resolution of complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
“It comes close to a holistic, overall view of employee experience,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday risk management group.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from lawsuits by employees."
Companies stopped taking ethics, values, and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after the collapse of Enron over the abuse of employee ethical rights, Quinlan said.
But it wasn’t until “social media shined a light on the whole thing” that companies began to realize that they couldn’t simply hide their skeletons in a closet in the online world.
“Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith,” Quinlan said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It’s a business model and an opportunity endorsed by bold equity investors backed by both startups.
As part of his February campaign, Convercent raised $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, eventually taking home $47 million in capital.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and raised $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research clearly confirms that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high salaries and interesting projects.
Employees want to feel that they are being accepted and valued and that they are devoting their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
“When people are happy at work, they feel that their voice is heard and that their work is rewarding, they strive for the company’s success,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money if the company is doing well and the company is thriving if its employees are happy.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market that ensures employee engagement and commitment to the company, it’s no wonder that there are plenty of investors who will support this effort.
According to experts on work culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is pointless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, big changes can happen.
And if the change does not happen quickly - in the worst case at all - it can provoke disappointment and disinterest of employees.
“Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations,” said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who has witnessed many companies relying too heavily on data alone.
“Because when you don’t get things done, employees start asking, ‘Did they hear me at all?
Are they interested in me?
If not, why should I care?”
Madison Reed, who now conducts employee surveys on a monthly basis, can fix the problem within a day, Errett said.
After collecting feedback from employees who were frustrated by the slow decision making and quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and initiate communication training to successfully resolve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important view of its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the long term in an industry known for its frequent layoffs.
“If you don’t strive to create a transparent work environment, employees won’t trust you,” Vitrano added.
“And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt."
