Creating a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
Scotney Castle played the lead role in the music video for the band Squeeze, and Margaret Thatcher also took refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
However, Scotney witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cozy spot on the Bewl River in Kent, UK, inspiring the curly Jamie Rhodes of York County - known for his penchant for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
“Looking at the writing of a man who is 300 years after death fascinates me,” Rhodes says with a serious face.
“When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection.”
The graphic novella A Castle in England documents the lives of families who resided in Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages until the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, it is not the first of Rhodes's archive-inspired books: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by British Library documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
If I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I've gone back in time.
I love the archives!
For someone so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the possibility of spending almost four months in the castle is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent his time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, going through archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on a wall and bottles that had been dumped in a ditch for centuries.
He walked around the grounds and explored the ruins of the old castle, talking to gamekeepers, gardeners, and occasionally artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
He drank whiskey and wrote.
Scotney's confidential history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained access to the documents in 2006 after the death of its last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, employees were only beginning to break into the archives, which Rhodes described as “aristocratics for many centuries throwing their hands around saying, ‘Bring it to the attic.’”
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps depicting estates: "You may think the land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were fighting over a birch tree.
Stop it, people!"
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story titled The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English Rebellion of 1381.
"I found a record of a rebellion in a castle in 1380, which was called the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book," Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually started in this area, and I thought the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they’re somehow related.”
Other stories are firmly connected with the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was not discovered until several years after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes’s favorite family is the Darrells: “I was intrigued by the male race - the men of that time were always in debt and spending money on things they couldn’t afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family have dealt with this by marrying rich or old wives - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to spin the heads of their heiresses."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes searches for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week retreat in the Finnish wilderness, where he took inspiration for his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was consumed by nature.
But it's a special place for Scotney.
“I was sad when I left,” he said.
“I was like, ‘Now get the hell back to real life.’
