Red meat, dairy and chocolate may alleviate symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
However, a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
An incurable disease that affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300,000 patients in the U.K. causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to eat meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps build immune cells that promote gut resistance.
The study’s lead author, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tilt to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting the body’s tolerance in the stomach of mice with a particular bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to make cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have found a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common component of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that promote tolerance in the body.
The more tryptophan mice had in their diets, the more these immune cells they had."
He also suggested that if it turns out to be the same for humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory gut environment.
Postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in the study of a type of immune cells promoting body tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice kept separately lacked the cells.
She deduced that one group of mice has a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mice’s intestines were tested using DNA sorting, and researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
The mice, which were kept in a sterile environment and lacked an intestinal microbiome - they did not develop this kind of immune cells - were given L. reuteri bacteria - and they formed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers bred L. reuteri in liquid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - free of the bacterium - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of these cells increased by 50 percent. After halved the doses of tryptophan at the same time, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: “We should all probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may increase cell population."
