White House Props Cost Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry last month cost $24,000, according to Navy records released by TIME.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a showcase of U.S. design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials surveyed a showcase of products from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a fork-lift truck from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the helicopter's presence less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) records said.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such an important event," HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy's deputy commander for aviation, the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the occasion of the show, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and will remain in place until complete clearance of the entire site, which was planned between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m.
The e-mail further stated that if there was a delay in leaving the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for the return flight due to working hours regulations.
The original crew remained at the scene that evening, along with a helicopter and a unit of security personnel.
From the records - obtained by TIME - it was not clear whether a second crew was sent in the end.
The Hatch Act prevents state officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible violation of this regulation.
"We wondered if this was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was in order," the commander wrote.
“It sounds like you’ve been blocked,” the deputy commander wrote.
This “Made in America” show was labeled an official event by the White House, and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political overtones.
While attending the event, the president pushed for health reform that went through the Senate and talked about trying to keep government regulations in check.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence for purely presentational reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after a presidential plane was flying in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
“The White House is delighted with the Made in America showcase, which showcases products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, deputy press secretary.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington area and on South Lawn and rehearse possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the crew's current training, a state official said.
The helicopter unit flew for another 11 hours on the same day as part of a “non-presidential support mission.”
The White House said no additional taxpayer money was being paid for.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not in any way involved in negotiations to expose the helicopter to South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep a budget record for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the parade is difficult to determine, the Navy said.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for the 2017 fiscal year, the reimbursement of DoD expenses for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below the stated amount.
"It's very misleading to quote taxpayers' costs on the basis of estimates for reimbursement," Walters said.
“These estimates include staff, maintenance, and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual cost.”
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD reimbursements do not include personnel costs, but include fuel price, maintenance, and contract costs.
The White House press secretary at the time, Sean Spicer, advocated the use of the helicopter for parade purposes.
“The idea for this week’s show is to showcase products made in the U.S.,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to the defense of our state and that they are providing jobs to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens are involved in making.
This is a fact to be recalled.”
It is not clear whether Trump, on his tour of South Lawn, was also looking at the helicopter. The only thing that can be said for sure is that he got behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House, Trump approached a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” said the president, “I own three myself.”
